# Triceps Brachii

> The triceps brachii is the **only muscle of the posterior arm** and the **sole extensor of the elbow**. It has three heads (long, lateral, and medial).

## 🔗 Bone Attachments
- **Origin**:
  - Long head: Infraglenoid tubercle of [[Scapula]]
  - Lateral head: Posterior [[Humerus]] (above radial groove)
  - Medial head: Posterior [[Humerus]] (below radial groove — deepest head)
- **Insertion**: [[Ulna]] (olecranon)

## 🗂️ Key Information

| Property | Detail |
|----------|--------|
| Origin | Infraglenoid tubercle ([[Scapula]]) + posterior [[Humerus]] (2 heads) |
| Insertion | Olecranon of [[Ulna]] |
| Action | Elbow **extension** (all heads); shoulder extension (long head) |
| Innervation | **[[Radial Nerve]] (C6–C8)** — all three heads |
| Blood Supply | Deep brachial artery (profunda brachii) |

## 🔑 Three Heads
- **Long head** — Only head crossing the shoulder joint; assists in shoulder extension and adduction
- **Lateral head** — Primary elbow extensor in powerful extension
- **Medial head** — "Workhorse" head; active in all elbow extension

## 🔑 Radial Nerve Relationship
The radial nerve winds in the **spiral (radial) groove** of the humerus, between the medial and lateral heads of triceps — a critical anatomical relationship for clinical injury assessment.

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Radial nerve palsy** — Humeral shaft fracture or Saturday night palsy (nerve compression in spiral groove) → **wrist drop**; triceps is usually spared as the nerve injury is often distal to its branches
- **Olecranon bursitis** — Bursa over olecranon; swollen, tender elbow prominence
- **Triceps tendon rupture** — Rare; fall on outstretched hand + eccentric contraction; unable to extend elbow
- **Triceps testing** — Tests radial nerve and C7 nerve root (reflex: triceps jerk)

